node.text: Which two names come to mind when you think of the biggest downhill mountain biking rivalries? For us there's no bigger rivalry than Steve Peat vs Nicolas Vouilloz. As you'll see, they haven't lost one iota of their riding ability, and with 11 World Champion titles and 29 World Cup wins combined, their competitiveness also hasn't diminished. It's awesome to see the two biggest rivals of MTB still riding, having a ton of fun on their bikes and sharing some stories about the good old days. Long live these legends!

node.text: For many people, mountain biking is a migratory sport. Once you get a taste for the trails, moving closer to ride every day is a no-brainer for those who choose the lifestyle. For @MattyHunter, migration was never necessary. He grew up in Kamloops, where the surrounding landscape was an ever-present inspiration for his own riding. Hit the link in our bio to watch Matt make the sport he loves look as good as it feels in the latest SHIMANO Originals, This Is Home 🔗 #ShimanoMTB #ThisIsHome

node.text: A child of the B.C. outdoors, @MattyHunter’s idea of a good day is any day he gets to ride his bikes. It’s never been about being the best, but rather standing shoulder to shoulder with his peers, never apart and never above. Matt has always just wanted the sport to look as good as it feels when he stomps his butter-smooth lines and gargantuan airs. Visit the link in bio to check out the latest SHIMANO Originals, This Is Home 🌲 #ShimanoMTB #ThisIsHome PC: @eyeroam

node.text: Blueprint started with a simple idea - to watch sections of trail come to life before the viewer's eyes. Once @markymath and team broke ground in Cumberland, BC, the abundance of dirt was the ultimate inspiration to challenge themselves to build something that pushed their creativity further than they had planned. The result, something special for all riders to enjoy; a hand-built, blue square level flow trail you'll want to lap all day long. Visit the link in our bio to watch an idea on paper turn into a trail in the forest ▶️ #RideShimano

node.text:
@markcavendish didn’t know he would be racing the Tour de France until a week before the start. At the end of last year, he didn’t even know if he would be racing this season. 

For four years, he’d been plagued by illness and injury. Most of the cycling world thought his days of winning bike races were over. Few believed that, at 36, he could regain the agility and speed that had carried him to so many victories. He never doubted himself though. His old team @deceuninck_quickstepteam decided to give him another shot. 

Over the winter, he worked very hard to get back to fitness. Four wins in April at the Tour of Turkey showed that he still had a sprint left in his legs. Then Sam Bennett got injured and Cavendish won the final stage at the Tour of Belgium. Deceuninck-Quickstep decided to bring him to the Tour. They had nothing to lose.

No one expected that @markcavendish would arrive in Paris with four stage victories. What Mark has achieved during this Tour de France is one of the greatest comebacks in sporting history. Reaching 34 stage wins, equalling the record set by Eddy Merckx.

On the podium in Paris, he pulled on his second green jersey. Celebrate and relive his 2021 Tour de France stage victories via link in bio. #ShimanoRoad #TDF2021
